#FeministPartner @chellaman’s latest project, “Big Deaf” continues to push the boundaries of what it means to be accessible, inclusive, and equal in this world. ➡️ See more at @whatthefuckisthischella.

“Unfortunately the continuum of disability is rarely taught or acknowledged leaving stereotypes as the only outline non-disabled individuals have of disability. With 15% of the world’s population being disabled, the individuality of our community should come at no surprise…” 💭 @chellaman

In this project, @chellaman reflect’s on his own deaf identity to navigate the reality of the continuum of identity. You can discover the perpetual release of “Big Deaf”  at @whatthefuckisthischella ✨

“The Beauty Within” is a short film following sisters Aaraf (@aarafxadam) and Abrar Adam (@abrawrr) on their journey to find their individuality, voice, and strength. A film by @kanxsuda
✨ We interviewed Aaraf for film release, see link in bio. 🔗  These women embody the power of Black female heroism through their vulnerability and unity. The silent interaction between these sisters showcases the power and perseverance that lies within each of us— the beauty within. The film features ballerinas Sydnie Collins and Audrey Malek performing as guiding fairies, leading the main characters through their journey of self-identity. The audio throughout is a poem written to serve as a reminder that “ Black, Indigenous and women of color must always be present, visible and amplified.” - @aarafxadam

*Credits in the Comments*

TW: Racism, Slavery & Indentured Servitude

Today’s attacks on abortion access have a long history rooted in white supremacy. The racist origins of the anti-abortion movement in the United States dates back to slavery.

Read on for excerpts from 'the Racist History of Abortion and Midwifery Bans' by @MichelebGoodwin for @aclu_nationwide visit our #linkinbio for the full article. 

"Just like slavery, anti-abortion efforts are rooted in white supremacy, the exploitation of Black women, and placing women’s bodies in service to men. Just like slavery, maximizing wealth and consolidating power motivated the anti-abortion enterprise. Then, just as now, anti-abortion efforts have nothing to do with saving women’s lives or protecting the interests of children. Today, a person is 14 times more likely to die by carrying a pregnancy to term than by having an abortion, and medical evidence has shown for decades that an abortion is as safe as a penicillin shot—and yet abortion remains heavily restricted in states across the country.”

“Today, as people debate whether anti-abortion platforms benefit Black women, the clear answer is no. The U.S. leads the developed world in maternal and infant mortality. The U.S. ranks around 50th in the world for maternal safety. Nationally, for Black women, the maternal death rate is nearly four times that of white women, and 10 to 17 times worse in some states.”

node.text:
Via @shoutyourabortion 
“…When I saw the words “pregnant”, I felt this instant feeling of panic, it was like the world around me closed in on me. I felt trapped. I am 31, engaged, in a stable relationship, a homeowner, and on paper ready for it–I mean we talked about kids and knew we wanted them – but everything about this fertilisation felt so wrong.

…We were not ready and decided abortion was the best option. It was a lonely decision, as a lot of friends were either desperately trying to conceive or expecting, or had kept their “accident” and now have a little one.

…It happened right before a public holiday, so I had to wait 7 days before I could go in for a consultation, 8 before I could access the medication. These 7 days were very emotional. I kept on going over HOW it could have happened? WHAT did we do wrong, WHEN did it happen? I kept on going over WHY I didn’t want to continue. What was wrong with me? Why wasn’t I happy? For the last 31 years, I’ve been fed happy “I’m pregnant” TV shows and friends. Nobody has ever told me that you can be absolutely devastated by it. 

…I was so disappointed in myself for letting this happen – as if I am the grand master of my cycle – and all of this was topped up with shame about my thoughts and decision. What I learned is, all those how, what, when and why do not matter. It happened, it is what it is. Not being ready is normal and not selfish. You are allowed to choose for yourself and I think it’s more selfish to set yourself up for something you’re not ready for, just because you’re fearing regret. Abortion is safer than continuing a pregnancy and does not influence fertility at all. Having a child is a big commitment. It is ok to decide that you are not ready, even if you have buts in mind, like in my case wanting a family at a later date. Making a decision based on your strongest feeling, in the middle of an emotional hurricane that throws you in many directions, is the bravest and strongest thing you will ever do, regardless of the outcome.”

Texas’ Near-Ban on Abortions Takes Effect After Supreme Court Fails to Act today

Support the fight to secure the right to choose. 👊 Protect abortion access. ➡️ Donate to our fundraiser in collaboration with @annie_wu_22 for @prochoiceamerica through this post. 

🚨 If you are pregnant and in fear, there are resources and people fighting FOR YOU. 
visit 👉 needabortion.org to get support in getting the funds and services you need.

“The court is still expected to rule soon on an emergency application from abortion providers seeking to block the measure, which is now the most restrictive abortion law in the nation.”   “Senate Bill 8 was signed into law in May by Gov. Greg Abbott, a Republican. It prohibits doctors from performing abortions if a fetal heartbeat is detected. Such activity starts at around six weeks, before many women are even aware that they are pregnant.” 

“Senate Bill 8, amounts to a nearly complete ban on abortion in Texas, one that will further fuel legal and political battles over the future of Roe v. Wade, the 1973 decision that established a constitutional right to abortion. The law makes no exceptions for pregnancies resulting from incest or rape. This law is especially difficult to challenge in court because it bars state officials from enforcing it and instead deputizes private individuals to sue anyone who performs the procedure or “aids and abets” it.” 

“The patient may not be sued, but doctors, staff members at clinics, counselors, people who help pay for the procedure, even an Uber driver taking a patient to an abortion clinic are all potential defendants. Plaintiffs, who need not have any connection to the matter or show any injury from it, are entitled to $10,000 and their legal fees recovered if they win. Prevailing defendants are not entitled to legal fees.” Source @nytimes

💡 About @prochoiceamerica The 2.5 million members of NARAL Pro-Choice America fight for reproductive freedom for every body. Each day, we organize and mobilize to protect that freedom by fighting for access to abortion care, birth control, paid parental leave, and protections from pregnancy discrimination.

node.text:
✍️ A note by @leksendrine on rediscovering body hair and body dysphoria. 📸 by @hamza.abouelouafaa “Three years ago, I started challenging myself with my body hair.”

“The first summer, it was the legs. Just trying not to shave before going out in general, sitting in parks with friends, being conscious of my hairy legs sticking out of the mix. Hearing friends make comments like “omg don’t look at my legs I haven’t shaved” when you can barely spot a hair, and knowing full well my legs are in full length.”

“The second summer, it was the armpits. It felt a bit more daring, much harder too. Documenting the process online made it easier though – cause people already knew and saw it in my stories, so when we hung out, I wasn’t afraid of the “first” look or stare. It was still much more stressful, and I still struggle with this sometimes. Never out of personal comfort, but out of being afraid of stares. I tried shaving once this summer, the weather’s so hot I thought it’d feel nice – but I was hit by a wave of gender dysphoria. That’s when I realized that my well-being outweighed whatever discomfort I might feel about other people’s looks in my direction.”

“The third summer (this summer), I decided to let the pubes follow the rest. This felt unbelievable. Even after having posted *the infamous photo* in January, the online vs. IRL life still felt miles apart. I really feel like there’s a big difference between Alex (IRL-me) and Leks (ig-me). (It’s mostly that I look much more confident than I really am, lol.) So showing them off online was one thing, but assuming them out in public, with people I know and don’t know, with friends and even family was a daily challenge. Documenting it really helped, though, and I’m so glad I have many of you who have gone through or are going through similar stuff.”

“Anyway, here’s my hair in the wind. Here’s me in my body. Here’s to how normal is it, as it should be. You don’t owe anyone any way of presenting yourself. You just owe yourself to fight towards being more comfortable in your skin today and you were yesterday. The self-acceptance journey is a tough and long road, but it’s a good one, and you deserve it.”

#bodyneutrality
